John Edward: language skills are a key skill for a global citizen
Learning outcomes in Scotland's private schools have traditionally been good, and this success has continued in 2018 as a result of good trial results. Success has been enhanced by individual and community success in sport, art, music and other community-based projects.
These schools of more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, represented by SCIS, Scotland's private schools council, aim to deliver a high level of service to their pupils as well as pupils' parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for careers of their choice, further and higher education, and global citizenship.
As an operator in the field of education who can design and implement customized study content, we have noticed that the status of languages as a popular and desired subject continues in educational institutions.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a person in a language he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to a person in their own language, the message goes to their heart."
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely only on the English language if we want to establish relationships with people in other countries.
From the latest trial results this year, we find that languages top the lists in terms of pass rate among private schools.
Sixty-eight percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade of A.
The data was collected from 74 schools belonging to SCIS. Based on the data, it was found that of the students who received the best grade of A, 72 per cent studied Mandarin, 72 per cent studied German, 69 per cent studied French and 63 per cent studied Spanish.
This shows that Scotland's private schools support foreign language learning as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently optional subjects, but they are held in the same esteem as natural science subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), both in the private school curriculum and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment Agency found that 17% of situations where employers had difficulty finding a suitable employee for the job were explained by inadequate language skills.
The development of language skills is therefore even more necessary to promote the future career development of young people.
The more language skills are required for potential jobs, the more relevant these skills become in the global world.
If a person has studied a second language, they will have an advantage in the future from this lifelong skill, no matter what career they have chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner automatically puts a person with language skills ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 poll commissioned by YouGov, out of more than 4,000 UK adults, 75 per cent are unable to have a conversation in a foreign language, with French the only language known by a double-digit 15 per cent.
This is why investing in language teaching is important now for today’s children.
Knowledge of the languages of developing countries, in particular, gives children a better chance to find meaningful careers.
Within Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Several schools focus on traditional languages, while some specifically teach languages that are supposedly important to UK residents in 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Regardless of your child's interests, private schools always have several language options taught by specialized teachers.
Scotland's private schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At this time, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment, languages will continue to be very important for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be seen as "international communication skills."
Private schools will continue to offer this freedom of choice, diversity and high standards to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the head of SCIS, Scotland's private schools council
