While Ri repeated the familiar lament that Washington will not accept a phase-out of nuclear weapons, in which North Korea would be rewarded for every intermediate point, his statement is nonetheless significant in that unilateral disarmament was not completely ruled out, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri was referring to the joint statement Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump made at the first summit between a sitting US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12. In the statement, Kim asserted "the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" and Trump pledged to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has sought to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has insisted that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The U.S. insists on 'denuclearization first,' and has ramped up pressure through sanctions to achieve its goals by force -- even opposing the 'declaration of peace,'" Ri said.
"The notion that sanctions would bring us to our knees is a wishful dream of the indifferent.
But the problem is that continued sanctions only deepen our distrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans to hold the next Kim-Trump summit, which Trump himself stressed to the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings with South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: "If the party calling for disarmament were South Korea and not the United States, the situation would not have reached such a dead end."
Still, Ri's tone was noticeably different from last year when he told the U.N. General Assembly that targeting missiles at the U.S. mainland was inevitable after "evil President" Trump called Kim a suicidal "missile man."
As recently as last year, Trump threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea. This year, however, Trump lavished praise on Kim for his courage in approaching the abandonment of weapons, while still stressing that much work remains to be done and sanctions must remain until North Korea gives up nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump mentioned that he doesn't have a time limit: "If it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
