Charles Czeisler, a professor at Harvard Medical School who is working on sleep research at Brigham and Women's Hospital, who designed the course, believes it is the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler got the idea for the course after lecturing on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, 'Why am I only hearing about it now, in my final year of college?'
No one had ever told him about the need for sleep, which I found surprising," he told the Telegraph in an interview.
For the first time this year, the course will guide students on how the right sleep habits support academic and athletic performance as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor at Harvard Medical School and the university's vice president of health services, says the university ended up running the course after hearing about how students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the study week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, students are presented with a picture of a dorm room where the student can snap coffee cups, curtains, sports gear and books, thereby gaining insights into the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of sleep deprivation on athletic performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
In another section, participants are told about how long-term sleep deprivation can raise the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
"We know that this will not have an immediate impact on student behaviour.
However, we believe they have a right to know about these issues in exactly the same way they have a right to know about the health effects of smoking," Professor Czeisler adds.
All-night study marathons, Professor Czeisler says, are still a matter of pride, and modern technology and the ever-increasing pressures on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
"Getting enough and quality sleep should be students' 'secret weapon' against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a state in the brain that resembles starvation, which is why a person is constantly hungry," the professor points out.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemical and physical psychology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of the courses he taught in his first year at Harvard last year.
She says the course opened her eyes and provided the impetus to run a course covering all students on campus.
He hopes all graduate students will be able to complete a similar set of studies before entering a competitive institution.
