Almanac: Geigerometer inventor
Next, a page from our "Sunday Morning" Almanac: September 30, 1882. Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, a future physicist, was born in Germany on this day 136 years ago.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity. The invention later led to the development of a device known as a geigerometer.
The method became one of the mainstays of science, and the meter also became a central concept of pop culture. For example, the 1950 film "Coronadon bells," in which Roy Rogers and Dale Evans play scientists who seem quite like cowboys, fits well:
Man: "What on earth is that?"
Rogers: "It's a geiger meter. It's used to look for radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you place your headphones on, you can actually hear the effect of radioactive radiation in the minerals."
Evans: "Look, it's really cracking now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945 a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name still lives on.
