The Global Citizen Festival, which started in 2012, is a follow-up to the Global Powerty Project, an international advisory group aimed at eradicating poverty by increasing the number of people actively working to eradicate poverty.
To get a free ticket to an event (if not willing to pay for a VIP ticket), the public must perform various tasks or "acts" such as volunteering, send an e-mail message to a political decision-maker or make a phone call, or perform some other act that spreads awareness of the project's goals.
But how has Global Citizen fared, now that the target is only 12 years away?
Is the idea of rewarding with a free concert ticket a real way to persuade people to take action, or is it just one ‘clicktivism’ among others – the fantasy that you can change the world by signing an online petition or posting a tweet?
Global Citizen reports that it has recorded more than 19 million "deeds" for various ends as of 2011.
It says these actions have encouraged policymakers to announce commitments and principles that are equivalent to more than $37 billion, and have been used in a way that will impact the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group listed 390 commitments and declarations, on the basis of which more than $10 billion has already been spent or raised.
The group estimates that the funds achieved have already affected the lives of nearly 649 million people worldwide to date.
Chief among the commitments, for example, is The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based grouping of investors and executors committed to "helping children develop to their full potential." The group committed to providing Rwanda with $35 million to end malnutrition in the country. This was after activists sent them 4,700 tweets as a result of Global Citizen's campaign.
