Bernard Vann: town remembers First World War hero priest
The city is celebrating the Church of England's only Victoria Cross Medal-winning, soldiered-on priest as 100 years have passed since the events.
The Medal of Bravery was awarded to Lieutenant Colonel Rev. Bernard Vann on 29 September 1918 for the events of the attack on the villages of Bellenglish and Lehaucourt.
But Vann died from a sniper's bullet four days later without ever learning of the highest British Army honour he received.
Two of his grandchildren were unveiling the memorial stone at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, last Saturday.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Vann, says the event is "impressively symbolic"; the memorial was unveiled exactly 100 years after his award-winning grandfather's feat.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Canal de Saint-Quent "in very dense fog and under heavy field gun and machine gun fire."
Later, he surged to the front line and, "showing the greatest bravery," led the advance of the troops before storming off alone to field gunnery. In the ensuing battle, Vann downed three gun battery soldiers with his own hands.
Lieutenant-Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918 – just one month before the war ended.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather's act was "something I could never achieve like, something that inspires respect."
Michael Vann He and his brother Dr James Vann laid a wreath after a parade paced by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann says it is "a great honour to be able to take part in the parade" and added: "a great crowd of people are there to remember the glory of a genuine hero."
MMA fans waited all night for Bellator 206 – TV channel showed Pipsa Pig
Imagine a situation where you've been up all night to watch the highly anticipated Bellator 206 tournament, and the entire event isn't presented.
The programme for the event in San Jose featured 13 matches, including six main series matches, and the show was to be broadcast live in the UK on Channel 5.
At 6am, just as Gegard Mousasi and Rory MacDonald were getting ready for the ring, the programme switched to Pipsa Possu to the great dismay of viewers.
Some spectators were not exactly delighted after staying up all night for the match.
One mixed martial arts friend opened up on Twitter, describing replacing the fight with a children's cartoon as "some kind of sick joke."
"According to the law, the content in question was not appropriate for airing at six o'clock in the morning, so they had to switch it to a children's program," explained Dave Schwartz, Bellator's senior associate vice president for marketing and communications for the program switch.
"Pips Pig, yes".
Bellator director Scott Coker said timetables will be worked on to allow UK viewers to follow events in the future.
"I'm thinking of a rebroadcast to probably make the show work," Coker said.
"But it's six o'clock in the morning there and we can't get the programme aired until Sunday our time, which in turn is Monday their time.
We are working on it.
You can believe that when the program changed in their heads, the messages started going one way or the other and they weren’t all friendly.
We tried to correct the error because we thought it was a technical problem.
But that was not the case; it was a legislative matter.
I can assure you that this will not happen next time.
We will limit the number of matches to five instead of six, as usual. We tried to offer our fans more and tried too much.
This is a sad state of affairs."
Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt low because of his sexuality
Swim jumper and Olympic athlete Tom Daley says he felt inferior to everyone else because of his sexuality. However, this motivated him to succeed.
The 24-year-old athlete says she only discovered when she entered secondary school that "not everyone is the same as me."
Speaking on Radio 4's Desert Island Discs, hosted by Lauren Laverne, Daley says he spoke about gay rights to give others 'hope'.
She also talks about how after having a child, winning at the Olympics was no longer that important.
Longtime radio host Kristy Young has taken several months off due to illness.
Appearing as a guest on Laverne's first show, Daley said he felt 'less' than everyone else when he was young because it was 'not socially acceptable to like boys and jobs'.
To this day, these feelings, to feel less and different, have been a reality, and they have given me the strength and energy I needed to succeed.
He said he wanted to show that he was “something” so that he wouldn’t disappoint everyone when his sexuality was finally revealed.
The two-time Olympic bronze medallist has become a high-profile LGBT activist, appearing at this year's Commonwealth Games to plead for homosexuality to be criminalised in other countries.
He said he came forward because he feels lucky to live openly without repercussions, and wanted to give “hope” to other people.
The three-time world champion says her falling in love with a man – American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom she met in 2013 – "came as a surprise."
Daley married this Oscar winner 20 years older than himself last year, but says the age gap has never been an issue.
"If you experience so many things at such a young age" – she attended her first Olympics when she was 14 and her father died of cancer three years later – "it's hard to find another person of a similar age who has gone through similar ups and downs," Daley tells me.
The couple had a son in June – Robert Ray Black-Daley – which has resulted in Daley's "whole perspective" changing.
"If you had asked me last year, my life would have revolved around winning a gold medal," he says.
"You know, there are bigger things than a gold Olympic medal.
Robbie's my Olympic gold medal.'
His son was named after Daley's father, who died in 2011 aged just 40 from brain cancer.
Daley said his father never accepted that he was going to die, and one of the last things he asked Daley about was the tickets for the 2012 Olympics. He wanted to sit in the front row.
"I couldn't tell him that he's not going to be around anymore to be in the front row," Daley says.
"I held her hand as her breathing stopped. It was only when her breathing had indeed stopped and she was dead that I finally understood that she was not invulnerable," he says.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
"I knew this was something I'd dreamed of all my life – to jump in front of a home crowd at the Olympics. There's no better feeling," Daley tells me.
This was also the inspiration for her first song choice on the air – Heather Small's song "Proud" – which stirred emotions even as she was preparing for the Olympics, and which still gives her skin goose bumps.
Desert Island Discs is broadcast on BBC Radio 4 on Sundays at 11:15 BST.
Semi-fit Mickelson on bench for Saturday's Ryder Cup
American Phil Mickelson will break the record on Sunday by playing his 47th Ryder Cup round, but he will need to peter out appreciably to avoid the record round going down in history as a calamitous performance.
Mickelson, who is playing in the biennial event for a record 12th time, was benched by captain Jim Furyk for fourballs and foursomes on Saturday.
Usually the center of attention, the American five-time Major tournament winner now spent half the day as a cheerleader and the other half on the court trying to get a handle on her batting.
The 48-year-old Mickelson, who even at the peak of his career was not considered one of the most accurate drivers, is not an ideal choice for the tight Le Golf National course, where the tall-bodied rough punishes inaccurate strokes.
If the field itself isn't enough of a match for Mickelson, Sunday's ninth game will be up against renowned British Open winner Francesco Molinari for his accuracy, playing alongside rookie Tommy Fleetwood, who aims to snap a streak of all four wins this week.
If the Americans, who are four points behind at 12 entering the doubles, get off to a flying start, Michelson's game could prove extremely important.
Furyk has expressed confidence in his player but what else could be said in the situation.
"He perfectly understands the role he played in today. He patted me on the back, crunched me and said he was ready for tomorrow," Furyk said.
“He has a lot of self-confidence.
He is arguably among the best players and has brought so much to his team in the past, and this week.
I probably didn't imagine he would play two games.
I imagined otherwise, but this is how it went and this is the solution we came to.
He wants to be on that court as much as anybody else.""
Mickelson will break Nick Faldo's record for more Ryder Cup matches played on Sunday.
It could also spell the end of a man's Ryder Cup career, which admittedly was never comparable to his personal performances.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and seven halves, but Furyk says his presence brings something unspecified to the team.
"He's funny, sarcastic, witty, likes banter at people's expense and he's a funny guy that everyone likes company with," he explains.
"The younger players probably had a lot of fun with him this week as well. It's amusing to watch.
He brings so much more to the team than just his contribution to the game.""
European team captain Thomas Bjorn knows how long a lead can disappear quickly
Thomas Bjorn, the European team captain, knows from experience that a sizable Ryder Cup lead before the final day's doubles could become a bumpy ride.
The Danish player made his debut in 1997 at Valderrama, where the Seve Ballesteros-led side held a five-point lead over the Americans, but who emerged victorious with lime lines just about the length of their noses and won by the narrowest possible margin of 141⁄2 to 51⁄2.
"You remind yourself how we led briskly at Valderrama, we led briskly at Brookline, where we lost, but we won at Valderrama, albeit narrowly," said Bjorn after watching the 2018 team's 5-3 wins both Friday and yesterday, moving to a 10-13 lead at Le Golf National course.
History will show both me and everyone else in the team that this is not over yet.
Tomorrow we shoot with a big caliber.
We're going to go out on the field and do everything right.
The game isn't over until the numbers are on the board.
We have a goal, we're trying to win that prize, and we're just aiming for that.
As I have always said, my focus is on these 12 players who play for our side. However, we are aware of what is on the other side: the best players in the world."
Delighted with how his team's players have performed on a difficult pitch, Bjorn adds: "I never lick until I tip over in things like this.
Tomorrow is completely different.
The priority tomorrow will be individual performances, and that's when we'll be talking about different things.
It’s great to be on the field with a partner when everything is going well, but when you’re alone on the field, your player’s capacity is tested.
That is the message that needs to be conveyed to the players – tomorrow everyone will be capable of the best performance.
Now we have to give up the partner, who is allowed to go [to the field alone] as well and do his best."
Unlike Bjorn, opposing captain Jim Furyk will demand a better performance from his players as individuals than they were able to partner. The exceptions to this are Jordan Spieth and Justin Thomas, who picked up three points out of four.
Furyk, on the other hand, has had final-day turnarounds both ways. He was part of the team that won at Brookline before ending up a loser when the European team won with a "Miracle of Medinah."
"I remember every damn word," he replied to a question about how 1999 team captain Ben Crenshaw handed his team's ranks for the final day's tryouts.
"We have 12 important games tomorrow but we want to get a fast start just like happened at Brookline, or like happened at Medinah.
When you get it moving in one direction, it piles plenty of pressure on the middle games.
We've adjusted our line-up accordingly and we'll put the boys on the pitch the way we want to, as you know, we're going to do wonders tomorrow.""
Thomas has been tasked with trying to lead the defensive battle and will face Rory McIlroy in the most important game. Paul Casey, Justin Rose, Jon Rahm, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter are next in order to face their European counterparts.
"I put the guys in the group in this order because I think it carries through the whole tournament," Bjorn commented on his doubles picks.
Germany's new warship delayed again
The latest frigate in the German navy should have been commissioned in 2014. The ship is intended to replace aging Cold War-era equipment, but will not be commissioned until next year at the earliest because of faulty systems and exponentially rising expenses, according to local media reports.
According to a military spokesman speaking to Die Zeit newspaper, the commissioning of the ‘Rheinland-Palatinate’, the first ship in the new Baden-Württemberg frigate class, has been postponed until the first half of 2019.
The ship was due to join the fleet in 2014, but worrying post-delivery problems have haunted the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 are intended to replace aging Bremen-class frigates.
According to available information, they will be equipped with powerful cannon, missile systems for combating air and surface ships, and stealth technology, such as technology that reduces radar reflectivity and the detectability of infrared and acoustic signals.
One of the important features of the ship is its longer maintenance interval – the new frigates should be able to operate at sea for up to two years without calling at home port.
However, continuing delays mean that state-of-the-art warships, said to be designed to improve German influence in overseas territories, are already obsolete by the time they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The ill-fated F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German navy refused to officially commission the vessel and returned it to Blohm & Voss' shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the Navy has returned a ship since it was delivered.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but there has been talk in the German media of essential "software and equipment failures" that make the warship unfit for combat missions.
The software deficiencies are particularly important because the Baden-Württemberg-class ships have a crew size of around 120, which is only half of the crew of the older Bremen-class frigates.
It also emerged that the ship is noticeably overweight, reducing its performance and limiting the fleet's scope for subsequent upgrades.
With a capacity of 7,000 tonnes, the Rhineland-Palatinate is believed to be twice the weight of similar class ships used by Germany in World War II.
In addition to faulty hardware, the price tag for the entire project is also becoming a problem.
The price is reported to have risen to a stunning €3.1bn, compared with an initial price of €2.2bn.
Problems with making the new frigates available have emerged amid recent warnings that Germany's maritime power is shrinking.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defence committee, pointed out earlier this year that the navy's usable ships "are running low."
The authority said the problem has grown over time because old vessels have been taken out of service but no new ones have been delivered to replace them.
He lamented the fact that no Baden-Württemberg-class frigates could have been commissioned by the navy.
Environmental group eavesdrops on bats' hidden lives
A new study being carried out in an area in the Scottish Highlands aims to find out how bats make use of the terrain when hunting for food.
It is hoped the new research will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation measures.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will observe bunting and dwarf bats, as well as ear moths and waterfowl in the grounds of the Inverewe Garden, a botanical garden in Wester Ross.
In the study, special recording devices are placed at important points in the area to monitor bat activity during the season.
The organization's employees and volunteers also perform mobile measurements using portable observation devices.
The frequencies of the pronunciations and the species concerned are verified by expert analysis.
Based on the results, a habitat map and report is created in which the behaviour of bats can be presented in a picture that follows the scale of the area.
Rob Dewar, the organisation's conservation adviser hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats, and how different species exploit them.
The information helps in the planning of habitat areas, such as the creation of meadows and the management of forest areas, taking into account bats and related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK as a whole have declined substantially over the past 100 years.
Construction and earthworks threaten bat resting places and habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can flypapers and certain chemicals used in building materials, as well as attacks by pet cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, due to nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful for catching prey than their eyes.
Bats use advanced echolocation technology to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The National Trust for Scotland is an organisation dedicated to protecting the rural environment, maintaining more than 270 historic buildings, 38 remarkable gardens and 76,000 acres across the country – and they take bats seriously.
It employs ten experts who regularly carry out surveys, spot checks and, in some cases, animal rescues.
The organisation has even established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat-only reserve on the grounds of Threave Manor in Dumfries and Galloway. Eight of Scotland's ten bat species are found in the area.
Farm manager David Thompson says the area is ideal for bats.
"Threave suits bats very well," he says.
"We have old buildings and trees and overall a good living environment.
Not everything is known about bats yet, so our work here and in other areas of the organization helps us better understand what bats need to thrive."
He stresses the importance of checking buildings for bats before undertaking remediation work, as the disposal of a single bat resting place can inadvertently cause the death of up to 400 female bats and chicks and wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are protected animals and killing, disturbing or destroying their resting places is prohibited.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer for bat conservation, is encouraging the public to get involved in conservation work.
He says: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and we don't yet know how their populations will fare."
Ronaldo denies rape allegations while lawyers prepare case against German magazine
Cristiano Ronaldo has branded the rape allegations against him "fake news" and says people want to "advertise themselves" by using his name.
Ronaldo's lawyers have taken action to try Der Spiegel, the German magazine that published the allegations.
The Portugal and Juventus attacker has been accused of raping Kathryn Mayorga, an American woman, in a Las Vegas hotel in 2009.
He allegedly paid the victim $375,000 for nondisclosure, Der Spiegel reported Friday.
