That's normal.
They want to be famous by using my name, it's part of this profession.
I'm a happy man and everything is fine," the player continued with a smile.
Ronaldo's lawyers are preparing to sue Der Spiegel over what they have called what Reuters news agency called "invalid reporting of privacy-related suspicions."
Lawyer Christian Schertz says the player is demanding restitution for "mental suffering in accordance with the seriousness of the violation, which means probably the most serious violation of personal rights in recent years."
The alleged incident is said to have taken place in June 2009 in a suite at the Palms Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas.
Ronaldo and Mayorga reportedly met at a nightclub and moved into the player's room, where he allegedly raped her anally, according to papers filed in Nevada's Clark County Regional Court.
Mayorga claims Ronaldo got down on one knee after the alleged incident and told her he "was 99 per cent a good guy" but whose "one per cent" disappointed.
According to the documents, Ronaldo has confirmed the pair had sex but that it was a matter of mutual consent.
Mayorga also claims she visited the police station and took photographs of her injuries at the hospital, but later reached a settlement because she was "terrified of the possibility of retaliation" and worried she would "be subjected to public humiliation."
The 34-year-old says he is now seeking a reversal of the settlement procedure because he is still traumatised by the alleged incident.
Ronaldo was close to an agreement to move to Real Madrid from Manchester United at the time of the alleged assault, and joined Italian powerhouse Juventus in a $100 million deal.
Brexit: UK 'would regret forever' ending car manufacturing
The UK would "repent forever" if it lost its position as the world's leading carmaker after Brexit, Business Minister Greg Clark said.
He added that he found it "worrying" the announcement by Toyota's UK unit to temporarily suspend production at its plant in Burnaston, near Derby, if the UK exits the EU without a deal.
"We need a deal," Clark says.
The Japanese automaker says the impact of border delays will be reflected in job losses if no deal is reached on Brexit.
The factory in Burnaston – where Toyota’s Auris and Avensis models are manufactured – produced almost 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
"My view is that if the UK abruptly exits the EU at the end of March, there will be interruptions to production at our factory," said Marvin Cooke, chief executive of Toyota's Burnaston unit.
Other UK-based carmakers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have expressed fears over exit from the European Union in how cross-border trade will play out.
BMW, for example, has announced that it will close its Mini manufacturing plant for a month in the event of Brexit.
The main concern touches on what automakers say are supply chain risks in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line is run on a timely JOT basis, with parts arriving at the plant every 37 minutes from their suppliers in Britain and the EU, and the cars are made to order.
If the UK leaves the EU without a deal on 29 March, it could cause disruption at the border, which the industry says could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
Holding more than 24 hours of stock at the Derbyshire plant is unacceptable, according to Toyota, and production would be suspended.
Clark says Theresa May's EU relations plan is "precisely calibrated to avoid these checks at the border."
"We need a deal. We want the best possible deal, which not only amounts to success in the current situation, but it is an opportunity we have to take advantage of," he says on BBC Radio 4"s Today programme.
"Not only statements from Toyota, but also from other manufacturers show that we absolutely need to be able to continue with the series of supply chains that have worked very well so far."
Toyota can't say how long production would be halted, but warns that the additional costs would reduce the plant's competitiveness and ultimately cause job losses.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has worked at Burnaston for 24 years and is a trade union trustee at the plant, says concern is growing among members: "In my experience, the jobs lost will never come back.
A government spokesman says: "We need to set out a precise and credible plan for our future relations with the EU."
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein may be delayed again, White House announces
Donald Trump's challenging meeting with Assistant Attorney General Rod Rosenstein may "have to be postponed another week" due to the uproar surrounding Supreme Court Justice nominee Brett Kavanaugh, the White House announced Sunday.
Rosenstein oversees the work of special counsel Robert Mueller, who in turn is investigating Russian meddling in the election, Trump aides' ties to Russia and any action the president may have taken to obstruct justice.
Rumors have been circulating in Washington for months that Trump plans to fire the deputy attorney general, which would jeopardize the impartiality of Mueller's investigation.
Earlier this month, the New York Times reported Rosenstein discussed the possibility of secretly recording conversations with Trump, as well as the possibility of the president's removal on the basis of the 25th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution.
Rosenstein has disputed the report's data.
Rosenstein visited the White House last Monday, and the purpose of the meeting has reportedly been to remove Rosenstein from office.
But President Trump was visiting the United Nations in New York at the time, so the day of the meeting was announced as Thursday.
Trump said he would "preferably not" fire Rosenstein, but the meeting was postponed because its timing coincided with a Senate Judiciary Committee hearing at which Kavanaugh and one of the women who accused him, Dr Christine Blasey Ford, were both testifying.
On Friday, Trump ordered a weeklong FBI investigation into the allegations against Kavanaugh, further postponing a vote in the Senate plenary session.
Trump's press chief, Sarah Sanders, appeared on "Fox News Sunday."
Asked about Rosenstein's meeting, Sanders said: "No date for this has been set. It could be next week, this week, it could be postponed for another week because of everything else that's going on in the Supreme Court at the moment.
It remains to be seen, but I always want to keep the press informed."
Some journalists might disagree with that assertion: Sanders has not held a White House press conference since September 10.
News anchor Chris Wallace asked why.
Sanders says the reason for the lack of press conferences is for reasons other than distaste for the "attention-seeking" of TV reporters, yet noted, "I don't dispute the fact that they are attention-seeking."
Sanders, however, suggested that direct contacts between Trump and the press would increase.
"The president holds more question hours than any president before him," he says, adding without quoting evidence yet: "We've checked those numbers."
"There will still be press conferences," Sanders said, but "it's infinitely better if the media has the opportunity to ask questions directly to the president of the United States than to have a conversation with me.
We often try to act this way and you've seen us act this way a number of times over the last several weeks, and this is going to replace the press release so you can speak directly with the president of the United States."
Trump regularly answers questions as he leaves the White House or attends open-ended events or press conferences with visiting dignitaries.
Performing alone at a press conference is rare.
This week in New York, the president possibly pointed to the reason for this in his uninhibited and occasionally bizarre appearance before the assembled reporters.
The Health Secretary wrote a letter to employees of the Scottish Public Health System (NHS Scotland) from EU countries over fears about Brexit
The Health Secretary has written a letter to Scottish health system workers from EU countries to express their gratitude and wishes for them to remain in the country after Brexit.
Jeane Freeman, a member of the Scottish Parliament, sent the letter with less than six months to go until the UK leaves the EU.
The Scottish Government is already braced to cover the cost of applications for "settled status" for EU citizens working in specialist public services.
In his letter, Freeman writes as follows: During the summer, the withdrawal negotiations between the UK and the EU have continued towards the decisions expected in the autumn.
The UK government has also stepped up preparations for a possible no-deal exit.
I know these are uncertain times for all of you.
That's why I want to reiterate now how much we value the contributions of each of our employees, regardless of citizenship.
Colleagues from across the EU and beyond bring valuable experience and skills that strengthen and improve healthcare work and benefit the patients and communities we serve.
Scotland is definitely your home and we really want you to stay here.'
Christion Abercrombie undergoes emergency surgery for head injury
Tennessee State Tigers linebacker Christion Abercrombie has had emergency surgery after the team's 31-27 loss to the Vanderbilt Commodores on Saturday, Tennessean reporter Mike Organ reported.
Tennessee State head coach Rod Reed told reporters the injury occurred just before halftime.
"He came to the sideline and simply slumped into it," Reed says.
Coaches and medical staff gave Abercrombie oxygen on the sideline before placing him on a stretcher and taking him to the sideline for further evaluation.
A Tennessee State trustee told WSMV Channel reporter Chris Harris in Nashville, Tennessee, that Abercrombie is out of surgery at Vanderbilt Medical Center.
Harris added that "the type/extent of injury is not known at this point," and that Tennessee State is trying to determine when the injury occurred.
Abercrombie is a sophomore at Tennessee State University and is playing his first season with the team since his transfer from Illinois.
He had five tackles Saturday before leaving the game, making a total of 18 tackles this season.
Foreign buyers will be hit with higher stamp duty when they buy property in the UK
Foreign buyers will be hit with higher stamp duty when they buy property in the UK. The extra money will be used to help the homeless under new plans from the Conservative Party.
The change is designed to neutralise Corby's success in attracting young voters
Raising stamp duty applies to those who do not pay tax to the UK
The Ministry of Finance expects to raise up to £120 million a year to help the homeless.
Theresa May will be briefing today on the higher stamp duty rate charged to foreign buyers when they buy property in the UK. The extra money will be used to help the homeless.
The measure will be seen as an attempt to neutralise Jeremy Corby's efforts to attract young voters. Corby has made promises on more affordable housing and has drawn attention to the taxation of the well-off.
Raising stamp duty will be targeted at people and businesses who do not pay tax to the UK. The extra money from this will be diverted into government action to ease the plight of the homeless.
The surcharge - which will be added to the current stamp duty on top of the second homes and investment housing increases added two years ago - could be as high as three per cent.
The Chancellor of the Exchequer expects the increase to generate up to £120 million annually.
An estimated 13 per cent of new-build homes in London are bought by non-UK permanent residents, pushing up prices and making it harder for first-time buyers in the market for owner-occupied homes.
Many affluent areas of the UK – particularly in its capital – have become ‘ghost towns’ because many foreign property owners spend most of their time abroad.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson set out a cut in stamp duty as a way to make it easier for young people to buy first homes.
He accused big construction companies of keeping property prices high by buying land and failing to build it, and urged Prime Minister May to reject quotas on affordable housing to remedy Britain's "housing disgrace."
Mr Corbyn has published a striking series of proposals to reform the housing market, including limits on rents and an end to "negligent evictions."
He would also like to give councils more power over matters relating to the construction of new homes.
Prime Minister May says: "I said last year that I intended to dedicate my premiership to restoring the British dream – that every generation's life should be better than its predecessor's.
This means fixing our broken housing market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and build their lives here.
However, it cannot be right that people who do not live in the UK, as well as companies based abroad, can buy homes as easily as hard-working UK residents.
For too many people, home ownership has become far too distant a dream, and the shame of homelessness remains a fact."
Jack Ross: 'My ultimate ambition is to lead Scotland's national team'
Sunderland manager Jack Ross says his "ultimate goal" is to become manager of the Scotland team at some point.
The 42-year-old Scot is enthusiastic about the challenge of bringing the team that holds the north-east corner of the country back to its feet. The team are currently in third place in the British second division.
Ross moved to the "stadium of lights" this summer after guiding St Mirren back to the Scottish Premiership last season.
"As a player, I wanted to play for my country.
I got into the second team and that was it," Ross tells BBC: Scotland's Sportsound broadcast.
"As a kid I used to watch Scotland games with my dad a lot of the time at Hampden, and that's something that's always drawn me back.
This is the kind of opportunity you only get if you're successful as a club manager".
Rossi's predecessors as Sunderland manager include Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former Alloa Athletic director says he was not concerned about stepping into the shoes of his prominent predecessors at a club of great stature. He has previously turned down offers made by Barnsley and Iptswich Town.
"At the moment I am measuring my own success by whether I can return this club to the Premier League.
Based on the structure and capability of the club, it is undoubtedly part of the Premier League," he says.
"Getting there won't be easy, but I'd probably only consider myself successful if I can pilot a team back to the Premier League."
Ross has only been manager for three years: first as Dumbarton's assistant manager and then for 15 months in the Heats' coach group.
He then helped Alloa emerge from relegation games in series three and elevated St Mirren from relegation fitness to champions over the next season.
Ross says he feels better now than at any time during his playing career with Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
"I was probably at an actual crossroads with my career," he recalls of the time he took over at Alloa.
"I genuinely believed I was better suited as a manager than as a player.
It sounds strange because I was playing well, earning moderately well and getting to enjoy some relatively big successes.
But playing can be tough.
A player has to deal with a variety of things every week.
