Red tide bloom status: concentrations dropping in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota regions
According to the latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, the number of algae shows an overall decline in the Tampa Bay area.
The FWC said more scattered areas of algae are reported from areas in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, possibly indicating lower concentrations.
Red tide algae blooms stretch along the coast for about 130 miles from Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
Ferries can be spotted ten miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but there are fewer of them than last week.
Red tide algae blooms have also been observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations were reported off the coast of Pinellas County in the past week, with concentrations ranging from low to high along the coasts of Hillsborough County, background levels to high levels in Manatee and Sarasota counties, background levels to moderate levels in Charlotte County, and background levels to high levels along the coasts of Lee's district friction and in Collier County, the lengths were low.
Respiratory symptoms continue to be reported in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier areas.
For the past week, there were no reports of respiratory symptoms from northwestern Florida.
